00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:03.220
Gabe Newell took to Reddit earlier this week
to quell a number of recent concerns

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:06.500
regarding an update to Valve’s Anti-Cheat service.

00:05:06.830 --> 00:05:10.800
The update in question was noticed and
highlighted by Reddit user “theonlybond”

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.530
in the early part of last week,

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:16.180
who posted about how the version of VAC
used in Counter-Strike: Global Offensive

00:05:16.180 --> 00:05:20.440
now features the ability to read through
all of a player’s DNS cache entries

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:23.180
before reporting back to Valve with the information.

00:05:23.450 --> 00:05:26.510
Reddit users began to speculate about the use of this service

00:05:26.510 --> 00:05:29.950
and how Valve could potentially be harvesting personal information.

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:33.760
However, while this does sound
rather worrying at face value, fear not,

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:38.340
as Gabe himself stepped in to discuss the
new functionality and how it was used.

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:41.860
Gabe describes how the system was
only in use for around 13 days

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:47.450
before being deactivated after cheat providers
identified easy workarounds to avoid detection.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:52.050
Rest assured, however, as, while the system
was publicly active for just under two weeks,

00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:55.610
the system was only used to target known or suspected hackers,

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:59.680
helping Valve to permanently ban 570 cheaters as a result.

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:04.670
In actual fact, the service did not take all of the
DNS information from an entire machine,

00:06:04.670 --> 00:06:09.740
instead trying to identify particularly suspicious
instances of cheat and hack mechanisms

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:14.450
“phoning home” to certain websites before banning
the user for having the cheat enabled.

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:19.420
Both posts contain a whole lot of in-depth information
that we’re really not going to get into right now,

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.530
mainly because we don’t understand half of it,

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:26.130
so Gabe helpfully left a brief Q&amp;A at the base
of his message, which reads as follows.

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:29.570
"1) Do we send your browsing history to Valve? No."

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:34.530
"2) Do we care what porn sites you visit?
Oh, dear god, no. My brain just melted."

00:06:34.990 --> 00:06:38.200
"3) Is Valve using its market success to go evil?"

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.680
"I don’t think so, but you have to
make the call if we are trustworthy."

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:44.270
"We try really hard to earn and keep your trust."

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:48.390
Well done, everyone... Panicking about your
internet browser history made Gabe lose his mind.

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:49.410
Good job.

